  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization of Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes in India, which was announced on November 8, 2016, the old notes ceased to be legal tender. This means they could no longer be used for transactions. Here\u2019s what typically happens to old notes after demonetization:\n\n1. **Exchange Period**: The government usually provides a window of time during which the old notes can be exchanged for new currency at banks or designated centers. In the case of the 2016 demonetization, this exchange period was limited and subject to certain conditions.\n\n2. **Deposit in Bank Accounts**: People were also allowed to deposit the old notes into their bank accounts during a specified period. However, large deposits were scrutinized to check for undisclosed income or black money.\n\n3. **Expiration**: After the exchange and deposit period ends, the old notes are no longer valid and cannot be used for any transactions. They essentially become worthless pieces of paper.\n\n4. **Destruction**: The banks collect the old notes and send them to the central bank (Reserve Bank of India, in this case). The central bank then verifies and processes these notes, and ultimately destroys them.\n\n5. **Exceptions**: In some cases, the government may allow for a grace period or special arrangements for specific groups of people, such as those who were abroad during the demonetization period.\n\n6. **Collector\u2019s Items**: Over time, some demonetized notes may become collector\u2019s items and hold value in the numismatic (currency collecting) market.\n\nThe 2016 demonetization in India was a significant economic event aimed at curbing black money, counterfeit currency, and promoting digital transactions. Post-demonetization, new Rs. 500 and Rs. 2000 notes were introduced into circulation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
